proof.p:
Since \set{\vectorlist{x}{k}} is a linearly dependent set there must be scalars, \scalarlist{a}{k}, not all zero (), so that

                    \zerovector=\lincombo{a}{x}{k}
                .

Let \vect{x}\neq\zerovector be one eigenvector of A for \lambda.  Then we proceed by induction on s (Proof Technique).  First, for s=0, employing  and  to establish the base case,
                    A^s\vect{x}=A^0\vect{x}=I_n\vect{x}=\vect{x}=1\vect{x}=\lambda^0\vect{x}=\lambda^s\vect{x}
                .  So \lambda^s is an eigenvalue of A^s in this special case.  For the induction step, we assume the theorem is true for s, and find
                    A^{s+1}\vect{x}&=A^sA\vect{x}
                    &=A^s\left(\lambda\vect{x}\right)&&

                    &=\lambda\left(A^s\vect{x}\right)&&

                    &=\lambda\left(\lambda^s\vect{x}\right)&&\text{Induction Hypothesis}
                    &=\left(\lambda\lambda^s\right)\vect{x}&&

                    &=\lambda^{s+1}\vect{x}
                .

solution.p:
Since \lambda is an eigenvalue of a nonsingular matrix, \lambda\neq 0 ().  A is invertible (), and so -\lambda A is invertible (). Thus -\lambda A is nonsingular () and \detname{-\lambda A}\neq 0 ().  We have
                    \charpoly{\inverse{A}}{\frac{1}{\lambda}}
                    &=\detname{\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}&&

                    &=1\detname{\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{-\lambda A}\detname{\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{\left(-\lambda A\right)\left(\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n\right)}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{-\lambda A\inverse{A}-\left(-\lambda A\right)\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{-\lambda I_n-\left(-\lambda A\right)\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{-\lambda I_n+\lambda\frac{1}{\lambda}AI_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{-\lambda I_n+1AI_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{-\lambda I_n+AI_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{-\lambda I_n+A}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \detname{A-\lambda I_n}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
                    \charpoly{A}{\lambda}&&

                    &=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}\,0&&

                    &=0&&

                .So \frac{1}{\lambda} is a root of the characteristic polynomial of \inverse{A} and so is an eigenvalue of \inverse{A}.  This proof is due to .
